8a) Describe sexual reproduction in hydra.
Data.answer: Hydra, a fresh water invertebrate from the class hydrozoa and phylum coelentrata. They reproduce sexually when conditions are harsh, often before winter or in poor feeding conditions. During this form of reproduction, swellings in the body wall develop into either ovaries or testes. The testes releases a free swimming gametes into the water, which swims and fuse with any other individual, leading to fertilization. Then the fertilized eggs secretes a tough outer coating and the adult dies due to starvation or cold, these resting eggs fall to the bottom of the lake or pored to await better/favourable conditions, the eggs hatch into tiny planula larva, which attach themselves and finally develop into polyps.

Hydra has a sac-like body with a single opening, the mouth, through which food is taken in and wastes are gotten rid of. Their body wall is made up of two layers of cells with a gelatinous layer in between. The mouth is surrounded by tentacles that help to catch food and push it into the gut. Hence, during feeding, the tentacles around the mouth helps in pushing its prey into its mouth after entangling and killing them with the help of specialized stinging cells. Once the prey get into their body via mouth , the body cavity releases/secretes digestive enzymes/juice that helps in digesting of the food and after digestion, they are absorbed via the same body cavity and finally assimilated in the cells.

1)LOUIS PASTEUR AND THE GERM
Pasteur worked in the middle and the late 1800s. He performed numerous experiments to discover why wine and dairy products became sour, and he found that bacteria were to blame. Pasteur called attention to the importance of microorganisms in everyday life and stirred Scientists to think that if bacteria could make wine sick then perhaps they could cause human illness. Pasteur postulated the “germ theory of disease” which states that microorganisms are the cause of infectious disease.

2) ROBERT KOCH'S POSTULATE
The German Scientist Robert Koch provided the proof by cultivating anthrax bacteria apart from any other type of organism. He then injected pure culture of the bacilli into mice and showed that the bacilli invariably caused anthrax. The procedure used by him is that which is regarded as KOCH'S POSTULATE.
